The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, June 29, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 TVS Motor Company has posted an 8.2 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 138.40 crore in 2003-04 compared with previous years Rs 127.95 crore. Chairman and managing director Venu Srinivasan said the companys total sales grew 4.8 per cent to Rs 2856.42 crore, up from previous years Rs 2725.40 crore. The consolidated sales, after the transfer of engine components business of Lakshmi Auto Components into TVS Motor, stood at Rs 2882.87 crore in 2003-04.																								 Uco Bank has paid a dividend of Rs 48 crore to the government, which holds a 75 per cent stake. Earlier, the bank had declared an 8 per cent dividend for 2003-04 on its shares issued through its maiden public offer in September 2003.																								 Geojit Financial Services Ltd, a joint venture between Geojit and Kerala State Industrial Development Corporation, has posted a net profit of Rs 8.8 crore in 2003-04 compared with Rs 29 lakh in the previous year. Revenues, which stood at Rs 17.7 crore in 2003, doubled to over Rs 37 crore in 2004.																								 Leading industrial automation players have formed the Automation Industry Association (AIA) to facilitate global competitiveness of the domestic industry. The members include ABB India, Emerson, Siemens, Larsen and Toubro (L amp;T), Tata Honeywell, Rockwell Automation, Yokogawa India Ltd and Invensys India.																								 The Nasdaq-listed Magic Software Enterprises has set a revenue target of $60 million in India by 2007 and increase the number of partners for its two products in the country. Magics total global revenues for the year ended December 31, 2003 was $63.39 million.																								 Fujitsu, a Japanese IT and communications solutions major, and the Bangalore-based Federal Technologies Ltd (Fedtec) have joined hands to tap the rapidly growing set-top box market. The strategic partnership is aimed at maximising the strength of both the companies in targeted applications in the digital television space.																								 Vijaya Bank proposes to increase the credit flow to the agricultural sector by 30 per cent during the current fiscal, a top bank official said. It had also aimed at issuing 30 per cent more Kisan credit cards this year, executive director P. A. Sethi said.																								 Oracle and Red Hat has launched an Oracle-Red Hat linux enterprise applications porting (LEAP) centre in Singapore. The LEAP centre is the first significant Linux initiative in Singapore and the first joint Oracle-Red Hat linux solution centre in the world, a release said.																								 Tata Motors, a commercial vehicles maker, has unveiled the new LPT 909EX turbo truck in Tamil Nadu. The LPT 909EX is geared to meet demanding applications, both on the highways and within city limits. ADVERTISEMENT
